<subSubSection id="15DE5FE0FFBCEF7FFF42F917FCF6F865" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFFBCEF7FFF42F917FB9AF959" blockId="20.[151,1436,1626,2013]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FFBCEF7FFF42F917FEE7F904" bold="true" box="[199,338,1698,1724]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Comments:</emphasis>
All individuals were collected in grasses, both in the edge and inside the forest. Individuals feed both on fish food flakes and fruits, vegetables, and grass seeds when being reared.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFFBCEF7FFF42F95FFA97F8F6" blockId="20.[151,1436,1626,2013]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FFBCEF7FFF42F95FFEEEF8BC" bold="true" box="[199,347,1770,1796]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Bioacoustics</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="C5FF10EEFFBCEF7FFEEEF95EFE53F8BD" box="[363,486,1771,1797]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1489,1513]" captionTargetBox="[175,1423,181,1464]" captionTargetId="figure-17@21.[163,1425,181,1466]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 9. Meconematinae from the ParNa Iguaçu. A: Phlugis occraceovittata, male; B: P. virens, male; C: Phlugis sp. 1, male; D: Phlugis sp. 2, male. E–H: calling songs of Phlugis occraceovittata. A: sonogram of a sequence of echemes; B: sonogram of three echemes; C: sonogram of a syllable; D; spectrogram of the respective syllable." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6550071" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6550071/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Fig. 9E–H</figureCitation>
): The stridulation is constant, with sequences of echemes lasting longer than 10 seconds, produced in an intensity crescendo. Each echeme is composed by three diplosyllables that possess constant intensity. The calling song of this species was already described by 
<bibRefCitation id="3955719AFFBCEF7FFC09F886FAABF8F6" author="Chamorro-Rengifo, J. &amp; Braun, H." box="[908,1310,1843,1870]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="439 - 443" refId="ref30552" refString="Chamorro-Rengifo, J. &amp; Braun, H. (2016) Phlugis ocraceovittata and its ultrasonic calling song (Orthoptera, Tettigoniidae, Phlugidini). Zootaxa, 4107 (3), 439 - 443. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4107.3.12" type="journal article" year="2016">Chamorro-Rengifo &amp; Braun (2016)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFFBCEF7FFF42F8E2FDDCF8C9" blockId="20.[151,1436,1626,2013]" box="[199,617,1879,1905]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FFBCEF7FFF42F8E2FE1EF8C9" box="[199,427,1879,1905]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Dominant frequency</emphasis>
: 43.0 ± 2.7 kHz.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFFBCEF7FFF42F8CEFE4BF82D" blockId="20.[151,1436,1626,2013]" box="[199,510,1915,1941]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FFBCEF7FFF42F8CEFEF5F82D" box="[199,320,1915,1941]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Bandwidth</emphasis>
: 21.4 ± 1.8 kHz.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFFBCEF7FFF42F82AFCB6F801" blockId="20.[151,1436,1626,2013]" box="[199,771,1951,1977]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FFBCEF7FFF42F82AFE9BF800" box="[199,302,1951,1976]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Duration</emphasis>
: Syllable: 10 ± 1 ms; 
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FFBCEF7FFDA0F82AFDCBF801" box="[549,638,1951,1977]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Echeme</emphasis>
: 60 ± 3 ms.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFFBCEF7FFF42F876FCF6F865" blockId="20.[151,1436,1626,2013]" box="[199,835,1987,2013]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FFBCEF7FFF42F876FEEAF865" box="[199,351,1987,2013]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Mute interval</emphasis>
: Syllable: 10 ± 1 ms; Echeme: 90 ± 10 ms.
</paragraph>
